    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-11-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-11-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="61"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d61">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_GPM1">G/PM</gloss> files, lot 68 D 349, “Ivy”</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">United States Atomic Energy Commission Press Release</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d61fn1">A notation on the source text reads: “For immediate
                        release Sunday, November 16, 1952.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 456</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-11-16">November 16,
                            1952</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Announcement by the Chairman, United States Atomic Energy
                        Commission</hi>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d61fn2">In a memorandum of Nov. 12, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Executive Secretary <persName corresp="#p_LAYJSJ1"
                            >Lay</persName> informed <gloss target="#t_AEC1">AEC</gloss> Chairman
                            <persName corresp="#p_DEANGE1">Dean</persName> that the President had
                        that day approved the issuance of this announcement. (<gloss
                            target="#t_GPM1">G/PM</gloss> files, lot 68 D 349, “Ivy”) The hydrogen
                        bomb test had occurred on Nov. 1, Washington time.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Joint Task Force 132, operating for the Department of Defense and the United
                    States Atomic Energy Commission, has concluded the third series of weapons
                    development tests at Eniwetok Atoll in the Marshall Islands. Like the Greenhouse
                    series 1951, it was designed to further the development of various types of
                    weapons. In furtherance of the President’s announcement of January 31,
                        1950,<note n="3" xml:id="d61fn3">For text, see <ref
                            target="frus1950v01#pg_141">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1950, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 141</ref>.</note> the test program
                    included experiments contributing to thermonuclear weapons research.</p>
                <p>Scientific executives for the tests have expressed satisfaction with the results.
                    The leaders and members of the military and civilian components of the Task
                    Force have accomplished a remarkable feat of precision in planning and
                    operations and have the commendation of the Department of Defense and the Atomic
                    Energy Commission.</p>
                <p>In the presence of threats to the peace of the world and in the absence of
                    effective and enforceable arrangements for the control of armaments, the United
                    States Government must continue its studies looking toward the development of
                    these vast energies for the defense of the free world. At the same time, this
                    Government is pushing with wide and growing success its studies directed toward
                    utilizing these energies for the productive purposes of mankind.</p>
            </div>
